Bakit hindi ko raw subukang mag-enroll sa Online Education System, and then, na-curious ako sa nag-research ako online at doon ko po mas nakilala si AMA OEd. Sa gaya ko na fulltime sa trabaho, at noon ay nag-give up na na makatapos, dahil working student, mahirap sa schedules, lalo na in terms of financial, ay may paraan naman pala upang makatapos nang hindi mag-gigive-up either sa trabaho o school. 1) Virtual classes for harder courses like GMAT-111, STAT-111, et cetera. These courses are harder in general. Math courses are easier to understand if there's virtual classes being handled weekly. This will also resolve the unnecessary uproar happening in the forums of GMAT-111. 2) Self-paced program option for students who can handle coursework better than his / her classmates. This is based on UST-Angelicum College's system. I am a product of the said institution's self-paced program. I've finished two academic years in 9 months because I can comprehend material better than my classmates. 3) More practical activities. Courses like EAPP, RWS, et cetera, should require practical outputs since these courses are practical itself. This will utilize the students' skills on the said courses. 4) Anonymous student complaints. Some students are aware of concerns that should be addressed where his / her identity should not be revealed to the violator regarding violations made by violators so that justice can take place. 5) Course and mentor evaluation for grade 11 courses. I have noticed that some courses in grade 12 has course and mentor evaluations. It should be done to grade 11 courses as well so it can be improved. 6) Grade requirements for entering students. Home study programs are harder in general because we are expected to learn the material itself. Thus, we should minimum grade requirements like no line of 7's, above 80+ average, etc. 7) Academic recognition for SHS students. Students within the honor hierarchy should be recognized and be given the mandatory medals required by the DEPED. 8) Graduation coinciding finishing residency. We should graduate within the year we finish our requirements within the residency given not 200 days per semester. I do think that students will not graduation since we're attending college after that.

Suggestion You guys know that the your interaction with students are always just about checking of assignments (if any), enrollment (Gradeslip, loading of courses, payment, and activation) simply non-academic inquiries. These non-academic concerns I think is stated in the Student Handbook already and there are other concerns not yet defined. Why not create a facebook page (or a page link in the student portal) about announcements specific to a program (i.e. Computer Engineering Students like me). Announcement could be the following (because if all students will ask this one by one and reply to them each is so tiring and all of us have different pacing). This is like the General Orientation in traditional school. I think this will reduce your student concerns email inquiries dramatically. 1. Update on course availability with when will it be available (so we can plan our OEd life we assume that all courses are already available) . 2. Clarifications on courses (this can be committed since it can be part of course module guide). 3. FAQs

In lieu of how I got here, I suggest you continue to accept students without the need of entrance exams. I believe it is only right that an educational institution would encourage the enrollment of students, no matter their caliber, for it truly relies in their own desire to learn and develop that drives them to study and to enroll, so why hinder them if they don't reach expected levels of prerequisite knowledge? Surely, this same desire would drive them to study harder if they truly craved academic achievements, that they would overcome their own shortcomings. On the other hand, I also find the paying of tuition fees to be very easy. It doesn't force us to go enroll on specified dates and times, but rather, allows us plenty of freedom to enroll and start our course at our own pace. The instructions on how to enroll and pay tuition are also pretty straightforward and easy to follow. Please continue to keep this process pressure-free and hassle-free.

This is for all the subjects in general. I hope all the subjects can offer live/recorded lectures so to make the learners feel more like they're in a classroom setting. I've attended a recorded lecture in Computer Programming 2 and I commend the teacher for teaching well, cracking jokes and making the class more engaging. For video lectures, I hope that all the teachers can sound energetic and interested in the topic, not bored, and to not make it too obvious that they are just reading the modules. They could do a quick summary of the topic while covering all the important points to give a brief introduction to the topic, or they could discuss the topic in-depth and explain in their own words, giving their own examples. Teachers should also make sure that they are reading things right to sound more professional and not distracting. Music is okay and spices things up but don't let it overpower the voice of the teacher. I also suggest adding visuals to video lectures so it can be more interesting. I suggest the modules and quizzes be checked for grammar usage because some things are hard to understand when the grammar is wrong, leading students to get wrong understanding/knowledge. I was afraid this question would be asked. All problems I have had with modules, lectures, and assessments were typed into the class review forms. Those that I can remember off hand are: MATH211: There are a lot of problems in the modules where equations were not printed properly leaving students to see an equation having no exponents when the answer suggests that an exponent was, indeed, used. Also, the video lectures were absolutely useless in MATH211. They had no bearing at all on what the module was covering and gave no value at all to the class. The video lectures should show several examples of equations and how they are figured out with further explanations than were given in the modules. Finally for MATH211 there was a point where the assessments and quiz did not match the material covered. The exact chapter and what was being taught are listed the review I made for the class. PHYED121: The questions in the assessments and quizzes did not fully reflect what was being taught in the modules. Sometimes the questions would have an answer that was different than the module stated and sometimes it would ask questions about materials that would not be covered until one or two modules later. I brought this to the attention of the professor and instead of correcting the order or fixing the questions to reflect what was taught she added new questions that had completely wrong answers and also continued to ask questions on material that was never covered or would be covered in future modules. These are just the examples I can remember right now. I give a full review of the all classes in my class evaluations. To correct these and the other problems listed in my evaluations, AMA should start a through quality control check on all subjects covering the modules, presentations, assessments, quizzes, and exams.

Mentor helpfulness is very much dependent on the individual professor. My experience has shown that the professor for MATH211, CS202, and PHYED121 were not exactly helpful. For CS202: when grading an assignment where there were errors in the program the professor simply stated that there were errors and to fix them. It is quite obvious that if a student submits a program with errors then they do not understand how that part of the program works. Instead of simply saying "fix it" the professor should review that part of the code and give the students some tips and explanations on what is causing the errors so they can understand the error, it's cause, and how to fix it. For MATH211: there was a point where the professor asked for pictures of the assignments. When submitted, the professor refused to grade it saying that not all the information was there. 1: this is a computer college. The professor should have the work done ON THE COMPUTER not submitting pictures. Also, if there is a certain format or information that he want's on the assignment then it needs to be made clear what is expected and have an example ready so students do not waste their time doing work that will not be graded or be graded as a 0. For PHYED121: the professor tried to be helpful by answering my notice that assessments and quizzes were not reflecting the right answers or were asking questions about material not covered until later in the class. However, her efforts made the matter worse. The questions asked were wrong, questions were still reflecting material not yet covered or that were never covered in the class.

Preserve and protect the integrity of OED’s Academic quality by promoting better and stronger student output in the form of projects ( interviews, documentary etc.) , activities (debate, recorded public speaking, oration, etc) , essays, immersion. Hence, less quizzes, exams, and Long Tests. This is my proposal: Content Modules for Academic programs ( 80% Activities ) - Project Presentations - Debates, Interviews, Documentaries, Recorded Speeches; - Essays - Term Papers, Daily Journals, Analysis on Current Trends and Events; - Immersion in field related events and; (20% short quizzes and multiple choices Assignments ) - Sidenote: Content Team must readily provide explanations, along with references, of every exams to the concerned Mentor for possible complaints on tests' answers ( e.g. my request to re-check eleven quizzes and long tests for possible correction of answers was resolved after three weeks). Post A Student Concern ticket is a very good tool but this should only be closed if a correct action has been provided. A reply of forwarding the concern to the responsible mentor does not mean the issue is closed. A reply that the action will be done the next week does not mean that the issue is closed. A reply that the ticket is closed is not clear since it does not include the ticket number. Since a ticket is recorded based on a ticket number, the ticket number should always be referenced in all replies in order to ensure that the student will be able to follow which ticket is being addressed or closed.

I'm not an education expert, and the way I see it is but from a student's perspective. My observation does not necessarily regard underlying learning and course objectives. Having said the above, for me they would be: assessments and content. Re assessments, they're similar to traditional schools that have students memorize dates, names, etc. I guess that checks my memorization skills, but it takes away the focus I would have loved to have in actually trying to achieve the goals of a course, which are usually "to understand and be able to apply something". There are subjects that do this well (ex. EAPP-111 - the application of the modules in sentence structure), and others that I honestly find ridiculous (eg. ICT-112 - memorizing the headers of a website's column that were not mentioned in the module. I don't think we are expected to pay attention and memorize all words in a web page. It's not part of the course objective, and there's just no point to it as these are just titles to make the interface more user-friendly and have no importance in the learning outcome.) On another note, in HMRM-111, the activities had no mention of a grading system. There were questions, and I answered them based on my opinion. I don't know how my opinion was graded, or how the way I sang the hymn was checked. In general, the content, in my opinion, is really good in most subjects. There are some that are a bit overloaded (eg. ELSC-111 - videos are too long; PHIL-121 - we're supposed to read the references as well, without notice). There are those that are, I would say, quite imposing without sufficient grounds or are only based on a single/limited viewpoint (eg. "These are the best ways to do something"), or things that are not definite and still has some relativity in them such as "Chinese are better at business or at math than Filipinos". Again, I'm not an expert, but these kind of content might limit inquisitive and reasoning abilities.

I think proper coordination with the different department should be improve, because based on my experience during every enrollment, there is no coordination between the Students Support, Finance/Account Department and Content Developing Team. While a student is currently enrolled, at least they should be preparing the next subjects so that they can give a full load and follow the curriculum on time. This is such a great help for us who wants to finish their degree as soon as possible.

It's a bit unsatisfactory to associate logging in to LMS as something you need to do because you just need it. Coming from another university where I also requested these documents, the fee of Good Moral Certificate(e.g) soft copy alone is already P565 here in OEd. In comparison with my previous university (private), I only paid P600 pesos for all credentials already (TOR, Cert of Transfer, Good Moral). I am just not satisfied how the process works for requesting credentials, much more it's costs. Requesting for credential documents cost too much. Coming from another university where I also requested these documents, the fee of Good Moral Certificate(e.g) soft copy alone is already P565 here in OEd. Another fee of P600 is to be paid for a hard copy. That also means, another fee for Honorable Dismissal, TOR, etc for both soft and hard copies of the said document. I feel liked I am being charged double for something that has already cost too much. In comparison with my previous university (private), I only paid P600 pesos for all credentials already (TOR, Cert of Transfer, Good Moral). Besides the current rate of tuition fees in AMA OEd, please look into this as it reflects the opposite of the university's catch phrase afford-degree program.
